Description: A circular bread-stamp, with damage to the lower edge, and an applied rectangular grip, mostly lost, on the centre back. It has an incuse pattern: within a circle of studs, a date-palm in fruit. Pressed over a modelled form. Brown Nile silt with some black inclusions. Face varnished in modern times for an impression to be taken.
Curator's comments: Terracotta IV Purchased: Greville J. Chester. Late Roman, sixth or seventh century AD. Comparanda: See von Falck and Lichtwark 1996: 180, no. 168, five undated examples, very much more random in their representations of the palm, and presumably thought to be of Christian significance.
Bibliographic references: Terracotta / Catalogue of Terracottas in the British Museum (3310)
Acquisition name: Purchased from: Rev Greville John Chester
